, overlapping ways in which survivors of domestic abuse are forced to cope with institutionalized discrimination based on race, gender, sexual orientation, and immigration status. The book also examines movement politics and the feminist movement with respect to domestic violence policies. The tensions discussed in this book, similar to those involved in the #metoo movement, include questions of accountability, reckoning, redemption, healing, and forgiveness. What is the future of feminism and the movements against gender-based violence and domestic violence? Readers are invited to question assumptions about how society and the legal system respond to intimate partner violence and to challenge the domestic violence field to move beyond old paradigms and contend with larger justice issues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aFamily violencexLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aFamily violencezUnited StatesxPrevention. 0aFamily violence-Law and legislation-United States. 0aFamily violence-Prevention-United States. 7aLAW / Family Law / General.2bisacsh  aBattering Court Syndrome.  aNational Rifle Association (NRA).  aTitle IX.  aViolence Against Women Act.  aabuse and neglect.  aaccess to justice.  aalternative forms of justice.  aautonomy.  abackground checks.  abattered women’s movement.  abattered women’s syndrome.  acampus climate.  acampus sexual assault.  acarceral feminism.  achild abuse.  acongressional intent.  acorporal punishment.  acriminal justice.  acriminalization.  acrossover youth.  acycle of abuse.  adiscrimination.  adomestic violence.  aempowerment.  afailure to protect.  afamily court.  afamily justice.  afelony murder.  afirearms.  agender bias.  agender politics.  agender-based violence.  agun control.  agun laws.  agun vi